                                            <h2 style=3D"text-align: center=
;">Common Cooking Conversions &amp; Substitutions</h2>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>If you bake or cook, you know how easy it is to jump into a reci=
pe without pausing to read the ingredient list or instructions thoroughly.<=
/strong> While you can memorize many things, trying to remember a conversio=
n for an unexpected unit of measurement or wondering whether you have that =
specific ingredient on hand can make even the most seasoned cook pause.</p>
<p><strong>Instead of scrapping the work you=E2=80=99ve already put in, you=
 have options to replace the ingredients you=E2=80=99re missing.</strong> R=
egardless if you=E2=80=99re doubling a recipe or converting from metric to =
cups, these handy charts will allow you to convert and <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.feesers.com/resources/conversions-substitutions/#cooking_substitutions">=
substitute everyday ingredients</a> with confidence:</p>
<p><img fetchpriority=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone wp-ima=
ge-23591 size-full" src=3D"https://www.feesers.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/=
08/MG-cooking-conversions-chart-scaled.jpg" alt=3D"a cooking conversions ch=
art for dry and liquid measurements" width=3D"958" height=3D"2560"></p>
<h2 style=3D"text-align: center;">Common Measurement Conversions for Dry an=
d Wet Ingredients</h2>
<p>Nothing can stop a delicious recipe in its tracks like needing to conver=
t measurements. <strong>To help make your cooking process easier, we=E2=80=
=99ve created a cooking and&nbsp;baking conversion chart:</strong></p>
<h3>Dry Ingredient Conversions</h3>
<ul>
<li>3 teaspoons=3D1 tablespoon=3D1/2 ounce=3D14.3 grams</li>
<li>2 tablespoons=3D1/8 cup=3D1 fluid ounce=3D28.3 grams</li>
<li>4 tablespoons=3D1/4 cup=3D2 fluid ounces=3D56.7 grams</li>
<li>5 1/3 tablespoons=3D1/3 cup=3D2.6 fluid ounces=3D75.6 grams</li>
<li>8 tablespoons=3D1/2 cup=3D4 ounces=3D113.4 grams=3D1 stick butter</li>
<li>12 tablespoons=3D3/4 cup=3D6 ounces=3D.375 pound=3D170 grams</li>
<li>32 tablespoons=3D2 cups=3D16 ounces=3D1 pound=3D453.6 grams</li>
<li>64 tablespoons=3D4 cups=3D32 ounces=3D2 pounds=3D907 grams</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>Liquid Ingredient Conversions</h3>
<ul>
<li>1 cup=3D8 fluid ounces=3D1/2 pint=3D237 ml</li>
<li>2 cups=3D16 fluid ounces=3D1 pint=3D474 ml</li>
<li>4 cups=3D32 fluid ounces=3D1 quart=3D946 ml</li>
<li>2 pints=3D32 fluid ounces=3D1 quart=3D946 ml</li>
<li>4 quarts=3D128 fluid ounces=3D1 gallon=3D3.784 liters</li>
<li>8 quarts=3Done peck</li>
<li>4 pecks=3Done bushel</li>
<li>Dash=3Dless than 1/4 teaspoon</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Fluid ounces on the outside of a liquid measuring cup are not th=
e same as a weighted ounce.</strong> A fluid ounce measures volume while ou=
nces measure weight. While you can use dry measuring cups, it will make a d=
ifference in the outcome of your recipe, especially for baked goods.</p>
<p><a id=3D"cooking_substitutions"></a><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"ali=
gnnone wp-image-23592 size-full" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=
